[[Image:Map of the African Union.svg|thumb|right|Map of the African Union.]] '''African century''' is the belief or hope that the 21st century will bring [[peace]], prosperity and cultural revival to [[Africa]]. Among those who have spoken of an African century are South African politicians [[Thabo Mbeki]]<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/monitoring/360349.stm Thabo Mbeki's victory speech], [[BBC News]], June 3, 1999</ref><ref>[http://www.nathanielturner.com/africandiaspora21stcentury.htm African Diaspora in the 21st Century], Address by Thabo Mbeki, 30 June 2003</ref> and [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]],<ref>[http://www.dfa.gov.za/docs/speeches/2001/dzum0130.htm Address by Minister Dlamini Zuma to the South African Institute of International Affairs, Johannesburg 30 January 2001<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Chevron CEO [[David J. O'Reilly]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chevron.com/news/speeches/2004/2004-11-05_oreilly.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-06-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060312230508/http://www.chevron.com/news/speeches/2004/2004-11-05_oreilly.asp |archivedate=2006-03-12 |df= }}</ref> US Treasury Secretary [[Paul O'Neill (cabinet member)|Paul O'Neill]]<ref name=grandtour>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/2018267.stm Doing the Grand Tour in Africa], BBC News, 31 May 2002</ref> and celebrity campaigner [[Bono]].<ref name=grandtour/> It has also inspired a radical policy journal - African Century Journal founded in 1999.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.african-century.org |title=African Century Journal | accessdate=2017-04-20}}</ref>
